tspan.tspan: When I was a baby snake,
people took me from my hole and placed my fangs over some glass. At
first they were aggressive and coaxed me into releasing my venom. They tell me my
kind is what made this necessary.
But over time I became compliant.
They placed me in a somewhat
spacious glass case with a
warm rock to lay on. They
would feed me what I needed
and milk me of what they
needed. While they did this,
they would tell me stories
of what my relatives did to

text.tspan: them: how they lost their sight
because of us, how their heart

tspan.tspan: couldn't beat quite as
strong, how
they struggled to breathe
because of us.
I began to fear what I could
do, worried that by
nature I wasn't

text.tspan: able to be helpful. But what I had in my fangs helped them.
So I let them guide my head to the glass. I let them
cover my eyes as they pressed my
head onto the glass. I breathed slow
while they spread my mouth and took the danger from my fangs.
They continued to feed me, the frozen food taking longer and longer to thaw
each time. They took less care to manage the temperature of the food. As I

tspan.tspan: waited longer and longer to be
able to consume the food and slithered back
and forth in my glass case, they
relegated further stories of how my
relatives would swallow their
beloved pets whole, strangle their
small and weak, and take
the ability to move their limbs
away. I remained
complacent in an effort to not

text.tspan: be like my relatives. As I

tspan.tspan: continued to
become more
complacent so did they,
and though the food
got colder and colder, I
comforted myself
with the fact that I was
being useful and helping
to heal old wounds
between our warring
factions. After a
particularly icy meal,
they took me for
another milking.
low and they
caught one of my fangs
in their palm. At this I
was dropped on the floor
and the injured one started
screaming at me, how I could never
be trusted, how I was the reason
they weren't in world of worry-free
bliss, how I was the manifestation of
the devil itself. Their eyes were red,
their skin was red, their veins were
pulsing. I was horrified I could do
such a thing. I was carefully placed
back in the glass case. They kept me
at a distance now as if it was my
fault. I curled onto the warm rock for
comfort though it didn't seem to be
heated anymore, they must've turned
off the lamp as they left in a hurry.
That morning I was cold and alone.
One of the captors who helped the
injured one came back, tired and
unkempt. They tossed a frozen mouse
in my glass case and carelessly
left without latching the lid. With
the cold glass and the cold rock
and the cold food, my blood ran
cold and I realised why they were
so angry at my kind - they were
scared of me like I was scared of
me. Their fear of lack of
control over me was a
controlling force to their
anger. Having lived my life
till then under the control of
anger sourced from fear, I
decided I was no longer one
for it. With that, I knew I
could simply slither out to
the warm sun and the warm
food and the warm earth.
What helps can kill and
what kills can help. I
would make the danger
of my fangs available
should they consider leaving me cold food again.
